            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Schofield equation?</h2>
              <p>
                The Schofield equation is a set of predictive equations that
                estimate
                <strong>Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)</strong> from body weight,
                age and sex. BMR is the energy your body uses at rest to
                maintain vital functions such as breathing, circulation and
                temperature regulation.
              </p>
              <p>
                Schofield and colleagues derived these equations from a large
                dataset of indirect calorimetry measurements and they are widely
                used in clinical nutrition, dietetics and public health
                guidelines.
              </p>

              <h2>Schofield equations by age and sex</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator uses the standard weight-based Schofield
                equations (weight in kilograms). For each age band, a different
                linear equation is used:
              </p>

              <h3>Men</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>3–10 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 22.7 \times W +
                    495 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>10–18 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 17.5 \times W
                    + 651 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>18–30 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 15.3 \times W
                    + 679 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>30–60 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 11.6 \times W
                    + 879 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>&gt; 60 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 13.5 \times
                    W + 487 \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  where \( W \) is body weight in kilograms and BMR is in
                  kcal/day.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Women</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>3–10 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 22.5 \times W +
                    499 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>10–18 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 12.2 \times W
                    + 746 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>18–30 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 14.7 \times W
                    + 496 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>30–60 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 8.7 \times W +
                    829 \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>&gt; 60 years:</strong> \( \text{BMR} = 10.5 \times
                    W + 596 \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  where \( W \) is body weight in kilograms and BMR is in
                  kcal/day.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How this Schofield calculator works</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>You enter sex, age and weight (kg or lb).</li>
                <li>
                  The tool converts weight in pounds to kilograms if needed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Based on age and sex, it automatically selects the correct
                  Schofield equation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It calculates BMR in kcal/day and converts it to kJ/day.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you choose an activity level, it multiplies BMR by the
                  corresponding factor to estimate total daily energy
                  expenditure (TDEE).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>From BMR to daily energy needs</h3>
              <p>
                To estimate total daily energy needs, BMR is multiplied by an
                <strong>activity factor</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Bed rest / ICU:</strong> ~1.2 × BMR</li>
                <li><strong>Sedentary:</strong> ~1.3 × BMR</li>
                <li><strong>Lightly active:</strong> ~1.5 × BMR</li>
                <li><strong>Moderately active:</strong> ~1.7 × BMR</li>
                <li><strong>Very active:</strong> ~2.0 × BMR (or higher)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These factors are approximate and may be adapted in clinical
                practice depending on disease state, stress factors and
                treatment goals.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical use and limitations</h2>
              <p>The Schofield equations are commonly used in:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Hospital and outpatient nutrition assessment</li>
                <li>Diet planning for weight maintenance, loss or gain</li>
                <li>Public health recommendations for energy intake</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                However, they provide
                <strong>population-average</strong> estimates and may be less
                accurate for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Very obese or very underweight individuals</li>
                <li>Critically ill or highly catabolic patients</li>
                <li>People with unusually high muscle mass or edema</li>
                <li>
                  Infants and very young children (special pediatric equations
                  are preferred)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                When available, <strong>indirect calorimetry</strong> remains
                the gold standard for measuring energy expenditure.
              </p>

              <h2>Example calculation</h2>
              <p>Consider a 35-year-old man weighing 80&nbsp;kg.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Age band: 30–60 years (male)</li>
                <li>Equation: \( \text{BMR} = 11.6 \times W + 879 \)</li>
                <li>
                  Calculation: \( 11.6 \times 80 + 879 = 1{,}807
                  \,\text{kcal/day (approx.)} \)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If he is moderately active (factor 1.7), estimated daily energy
                needs:
              </p>
              <p class="formula-box">
                \( \text{TDEE} \approx 1{,}807 \times 1.7 \approx 3{,}072
                \,\text{kcal/day} \)
              </p>

              <h2>Safety note</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is intended for educational and general planning
                purposes. It does not replace medical advice. For patients with
                complex medical conditions, always consult a registered
                dietitian, physician or clinical nutrition specialist.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Frequently Asked Questions
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >What is the Schofield equation used for?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    It is used to estimate Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) from
                    weight, age and sex. Clinicians and dietitians then apply
                    activity and stress factors to determine total energy
                    requirements for diet planning, enteral/parenteral nutrition
                    and weight management.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Can I use the Schofield equation for children?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Yes, the Schofield equations include age bands for children
                    aged 3–10 and 10–18 years, with separate formulas for boys
                    and girls. For infants and toddlers under 3 years,
                    pediatric-specific equations or indirect calorimetry are
                    preferred.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >How does Schofield compare to Harris–Benedict or
                      Mifflin–St Jeor?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    All three are predictive BMR equations but were derived from
                    different populations and variables. Harris–Benedict and
                    Mifflin–St Jeor include both weight and height, while the
                    weight-based Schofield equations used here rely only on
                    weight, age and sex. Some guidelines prefer Schofield for
                    certain age groups, while others favor Mifflin–St Jeor in
                    adults with overweight or obesity.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium"
                      >Does this calculator account for illness or stress
                      factors?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    No. It provides baseline BMR and optional activity-adjusted
                    energy needs. In clinical practice, additional stress or
                    injury factors (e.g., for sepsis, burns, trauma) may be
                    applied on top of BMR. Those should be determined by a
                    qualified clinician using current guidelines.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
